Value.value: Your inspection of the pole and the skulls impaled upon it leads you to believe these are human skulls of varying sizes. It's hard to tell how long they have been here, however.

These humanoid skulls have been here for quite a long time, perhaps even decades. To you, the impaled human skulls makes sense; you are dealing with Trogdolytes, after all, and humans are one of their favorite prey.

You see human skulls impaled almost meticulously along the length of a carved oak pole. You can tell the pole itself was once the shaft of a spear, judging by the bit of steel left behind from the removal of the spear's head. The skulls are all from adults and have been boiled to remove the flesh that was once on them. All in all, typical of Trogdolytes and their morbid rituals.

value.0: While this ladder has clearly seen many seasons, it still looks strong enough to hold your weight and will lead you back to the swamps.
This is just a grass. Nothing to explore.
This is just a grass. Nothing to explore.

After you climb down a chimney shaft from the access in the swamps above, the overgrown ruins laid before you stretch on as far as you can see in the dim lighting. The stench of decay and death assault your nose, followed by the tang of rust and mold.

Value.value: A small mechaical gear, likely from one of the many old, worn down machines littering the ruins. Or scavenged from somewhere else.

This chunk of metal is obviously a gear from one of the numerous machines that can be seen broken down throughout the ruins you've traveled through. Rust covers the gear, making it well known that it has been in the elements for quite a long time..

You can tell this gear came from a broken down and overgrown machine not too far away. By the looks of it and the machine, when put together, they were used for smelting steel and you come to realize you are standing in the middle of a dilapidated steel mill.

value.0: Scraps and detritus cling together in an unsightly pile.
Pile of Garbage [Click to inspect further...]

Value.value: A pile of junk, it looks like. Bits of weapons and steel can be found, if you looked hard enough.

In the pile of junk you can pick out garbage that has flown in by way of the swamp above from Cordor's sewage runoff. Warped pieces of steel and weapons made from steel can be found, as well. Knowing what you do of Trogdolytes, this isn't any thing new. Trogdolytes are hoarders by nature and favor steel the most.

Known for their love of steel, the sheer amount of the metal you see within this pile of garbage gathered by the Trogdolytes makes sense. Seeing as the Trogdolytes are hoarders by nature you're not surprised by what you find lying in the pile, or that you find piles just like it through the ruins and caves. Why, you can even see discarded newspapers from Cordor and lots of other stuff that came from the sewage runoff! Most of it you probably don't want to touch, lest risk infection or disease.

value.0: A mine cart covered in rust.
Rusted Mine Cart [Click to inspect further...]

Value.value: Covered in rust, this mine cart has obviously been here for a long time and exposed to the elements. Given your trip through the caverns so far, you know this was likely dragged here by the Trogdolytes.

Knowing mine carts are used to transport large loads of ore and metal from a mining site to the smelter, you find it odd that this particular cart is off of its tracks and haphazardly left to rust as it has. When you think on it, however, it makes sense. Given the love of steel the Trogdolytes have, you know this cart was seen as a rather large prize by one of the lizardfolk. The cart itself is made from steel, afterall. Judging by what you've seen in the caverns and ruins so far, your earlier thought was correct. You are standing in the ruins of a steel mill that collapsed decades ago and Trogdolytes have made it their lair.

Mine carts are used by miners to help them transport large quantities of metal ore back and forth. This particular cart has been taken off its tracks for some reason or another. After being left out in the elements as long as it has, it's nearly rusted to the spot it sits on. By what you've seen of this Trodoglyte lair so far, you're getting the feeling that the lizardfolk have made some sort of steel mill into their home.
